The '''great grain robbery''' was the July 1972 purchase of 10 million [[ton]]s of United States [[grain]] (mainly [[wheat]] and [[corn]]) by the [[Soviet Union]] at [[subsidized]] prices, which resulted in higher grain prices in the [[United States]].<ref name=Martha>{{cite book|title=The Great American Grain Robbery & Other Stories | last=Hamilton|first=Martha M.|year=1972|publisher=Agribusiness Accountability Project|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=313}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Great Grain Robbery |last=Trager |first=James |year=1975 |publisher=Ballantine |location=New York |isbn=0345241509 |pages=233 }}</ref> Grain prices soon reached 125-year highs in Chicago. In a 10-month span, soybeans went from $3.31 to $12.90 a bushel. Food prices around the world rose 50% in 1973.<!-- blacklisted link <ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyreckoning.com/the-great-grain-robbery/|title=The Great Grain Robbery - Daily Reckoning|date=August 9, 2010|publisher=|access-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref> --> The U.S. government spent $300 million and by unwittingly{{Says who|date=July 2016}} subsidizing the Russian purchases, this event helped lead to the U.S. government seeking more information about global agricultural output via infrared satellite intelligence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earthzine.org/2015/10/28/the-great-grain-robbery-of-1972/|title=The ‘Great Grain Robbery’ of 1972|date=October 28, 2015|publisher=|access-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref>
==Russian wheat deal or Soviet wheat deal== This event was referred to in U.S. media of the time as "The Russian Wheat Deal" or "The Soviet Wheat Deal".<ref>{{Cite web | title = Russian Wheat Deal | publisher = MarketsWiki.com | date = 4 December 2009 | url = http://www.marketswiki.com/mwiki/Russian_wheat_deal | accessdate = July 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = Luttrell | first = Clifton B. | last2 = | title = The Russian Wheat Deal - Hindsight vs. Foresight, Reprint No. 81 | publisher = Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis | date = October 1973 | url = http://research.stlouisfed.org/publications/review/73/10/Russian_Oct1973.pdf | access-date = July 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Alexander | first = Holmes | title = Who was the real villain in Russian wheat deal? | newspaper = Rome News-Tribune | location = | pages = | publisher = | date = September 6, 1974 | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19740906&id=XbEFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LjMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5222,714560 | access-date = July 26, 2011}} </ref> The term ''Great Grain Robbery'' is a pun referring to the "[[Great Gold Robbery|Great Train Robbery]]". Author [[Martha Hamilton]] introduced the term as the title of Chapter VII of her book ''The Great American Grain Robbery & Other Tales'', as part of an allegation that the U.S. government was robbing American taxpayers in order to support grain trading companies.<ref name=Martha /> The terms ''Russian wheat deal'' and ''Soviet wheat deal'' fell into disuse since the sales included corn, barley and oats as well as wheat.
